Conversation 8:
Mia: (Quietly whispering to not distract others) Emily, I couldn't help but notice that your exam paper is quite visible. I wouldn't want anyone to wrongly get the idea that you're enabling cheating. {Information}

Emily: (Surprised) Oh, Mia, I didn't realize. I've been feeling so scatterbrained lately... my mind has been all over the place.

Mia: It's okay, Emily. We all have those days. If there's something troubling you, know that I'm here for you, alright? {Affirmation and reassurance}

Emily: (Nodding) Thank you, Mia. It's... It's a bit overwhelming, you know? The pressure of exams, I can barely concentrate.

Mia: Sounds like you're feeling quite a lot of anxiety. It's absolutely normal, Em, especially during exams. You're not alone. {Affirmation and reassurance}

Emily: It's just... It's more than that, Mia. I feel this heavy burden all the time. I can't sleep well, I've lost my appetite, and I'm constantly anxious, even when I'm not studying.

Mia: Emily, I know we're in the middle of an exam right now, but I feel it's important to address how you're feeling. Sometimes, intense stress can lead to or be a sign of depression. You're not just a number on an exam paper; your well-being matters. {Reflection of feelings, Information}

Emily: Do.. Do you really think I could be dealing with depression, Mia?

Mia: I am no mental health expert, Emily, but I think it would be a great idea to speak to one. Even as a nurse, addressing mental health is not my domain, but I can accompany you or support you in seeking help. {Providing suggestions, Information}

Emily: (Sighs) I think you might be right, Mia. I've been ignoring this for a while now.

Mia: It's a brave step to acknowledge it, Emily. Remember, seeking help isn't a sign of weakness; it's a sign of strength. I'm here for you, and we'll work through this together. {Affirmation and reassurance, Providing suggestions}
